Pompey's great theatre, the first permanent one built at Rome, appears to have been finished the year of Lucretius’ death; but the temporary wooden ones of which he had experience were probably constructed on a similar plan. Q. Catulus is recorded to have first spread these awnings: Pliny xlx 23, who calls them carbasina vela. [But see Friedlaender Sitteng. 11 p. 536; and Archaeological Journal vol. 32 p. 286 (J. H. Parker), of the Coliseum: ‘it is now clear that there was an awning over the heads of the spectators in the galleries and kept at the height of 20 feet above their heads by masts on which it was suspended. Those at the top were known before by the corbels that supported them, and the holes through the cornice at the top of the building through which the masts passed. We have now found evidence of similar masts at the bottom, supported by corbels in front of the podium. It is probable that the cords which carried the awning were also supported by the columns on the outer edge of the upper gallery‚ as the distance would be too long for the cords to bear the weight with no intervening support': p. 28? ‘we also there (on the upper wall) see the mode of fastening the masts on the inner side of the wall to hold them fast.
